1. Specification
Input: integer n >= 1
Behavior: produce sequence S[1..n] where S[i] is string "Fizz", "Buzz", "FizzBuzz", or numeric i per the rules above.
Output: array of length n where each entry is either a number or a string.

2. Algorithm and complexity
Algorithm: single loop for i from 1 to n, compute remainder tests using modulo operator in order described. Use i % 15 === 0 for combined check where convenient. Time complexity O(n). Space: O(1) if streaming outputs, O(n) if producing full array.

3. Implementation patterns
Signature: function fizzBuzz(n: number): Array<string|number>
Preconditions: n must be an integer >= 1. If not integer, throw RangeError. If n is extremely large, prefer streaming generator to avoid memory blowup.
Pattern (pseudocode):
for (let i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
  if (i % 15 === 0) emit("FizzBuzz");
  else if (i % 3 === 0) emit("Fizz");
  else if (i % 5 === 0) emit("Buzz");
  else emit(i);
}

4. Edge cases and error handling
If n is not a finite integer -> throw RangeError("n must be a finite integer >= 1").
If n <= 0 -> return [] or throw depending on API choice; prefer throwing for strict validation.
Negative inputs: invalid by spec.
Large n: risk of memory exhaustion if returning array; recommend iterator/generator.

5. Supplementary details
Variants: allow start/end parameters: fizzBuzz(start, end) with inclusive range and identical rules applied per index value.
Internationalisation: outputs are fixed tokens "Fizz"/"Buzz"; localization must be applied outside core algorithm.
Testing: assert exact sequence for small n (1..15) including combined positions 3,5,15.

